\title{Inverse Trig. Functions (Basics)}
Meaning of $\sin^{-1}x,\cos^{-1}
x$ etc ;domains and principal ranges

reason.tex:
%text A lot of people mistakenly assume that \[ \qquad \sin^{-1}x = \dfrac{1}{\sin x} \] $\sin^{-1} x, \cos^{-1}x$ etc are angles! By definition, $\sin\theta = x \implies \sin^{-1} x=\theta$ Same goes for $\cos^{-1}x$ or $\tan^{-1}x$ etc. $\theta$ in the above equation belongs to what is called the \underline\text{principal range} It is the \underline\text{smallest range of angles} that will give all possible values for a trigonometric function -- as summarized in the table below
% \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{MMM}
\hline \text{Function} & x \in & \text{Principal Range} \\ \hline y = \sin^{-1}x & [-1,1] & \left[ -\frac\pi{2},\frac\pi{2} \right] \\ \hline y = \cos^{-1} x & [-1,1] & [0,\pi] \\ \hline y = \tan^{-1} x & \mathbb{R} & \left( -\frac\pi{2},\frac\pi{2} \right) \\ \hline y = \csc^{-1}x & \mathbb{R}-(-1,1) & \left[ -\frac\pi{2},\frac\pi{2} \right] - \lbrace 0\rbrace \\ \hline y = \sec^{-1}x & \mathbb{R}-(-1,1) & \left[ 0,\pi \right] - \lbrace \frac\pi{2}\rbrace \\ \hline y = \cot^{-1} x & \mathbb{R} & (0,\pi) \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text %
